  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/decision/dr-cou1-noncannulated-accepted",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/actor/credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment team accepts the FEA modeling framework for the non-cannulated pedicle screw compression-bending COU based on the following structured evidence review. All 13 V&V 40 credibility factors have been assessed; all achievedLevels meet or exceed requiredLevels for the Model Risk Level 3 / Medium assurance context. Three ValidationResult objects document quantitative QoI comparisons: (1) stiffness E/uval = 1.41 < 1.96, (2) yield force percentage difference = 7.8% < 10%, and (3) force at 40 mm E/uval = 1.62 < 1.96. All pre-specified acceptance bounds are satisfied. The team acknowledges and explicitly documents several sources of low confidence and wide uncertainty: (a) material property scatter (CoV 14.3% for stiffness, wide 95% CI on yield force prediction spanning ±18%) arising from batch-to-batch Ti-6Al-4V variability; (b) model form uncertainty in the large-displacement regime contributing to the borderline E/uval of 1.62 for force at 40 mm; (c) modest sample size (N=11) limiting statistical power for inter-laboratory comparison. These limitations are not concealed — they are fully documented in the UQ records (mc-stiffness-90pi-noncannulated, sensitivity-yieldforce-95ci-noncannulated, mc-force40mm-90pi-noncannulated) and in the factor rationales above. The decision to accept despite these documented uncertainties is grounded in: (i) all quantitative acceptance criteria are met even when using probabilistic E/uval rather than point estimates; (ii) the model influence is Medium and decision consequence is Medium, placing this at Model Risk Level 3 where Gradation 2 factors are appropriate; (iii) the validation is direct (same device, same loading, same QoIs) rather than analogous; (iv) multi-laboratory replication provides independent corroboration. The wide uncertainty bounds are accepted as residual risk consistent with the Medium assurance level and the moderate clinical consequence (revision surgery, not mortality). This residual risk is proportionate and acceptable for the intended regulatory use.",
